The [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd), a [Welsh kingdom](/Wales_in_the_Early_Middle_Ages) that clawed its way into existence at the dawn of the sixth century, was less a fixed entity and more a persistent, often inconvenient, thorn in the side of anyone seeking easy dominance over [Wales](/Wales). Nestled in the rugged northwest, its [rulers](/List_of_rulers_of_Gwynedd) repeatedly managed to assert a fleeting dominance, frequently acclaimed as "[King of the Britons](/King_of_the_Britons)" before the inevitable internal strife or external invasion would, with predictable regularity, strip them of their power. It was a cycle as old as ambition itself.

Consider the kingdom of [Gruffudd ap Llywelyn](/Gruffudd_ap_Llywelyn), for instance, who briefly held the grand title of [King of Wales](/King_of_Wales) from 1055 to 1063. His unified realm was, quite predictably, shattered by a [Saxon invasion in 1063](/Timeline_of_conflict_in_Anglo-Saxon_Britain), a mere prelude to the more comprehensive, and arguably more irritating, [Norman invasion of Wales](/Norman_invasion_of_Wales) that followed. Yet, the [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw), a lineage seemingly as resilient as the Welsh mountains themselves, was eventually restored by [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan). This dynasty painstakingly recovered its influence, culminating in [Llywelyn the Great](/Llywelyn_the_Great) of Gwynedd proclaiming the very [Principality of Wales](/Principality_of_Wales) at the [Aberdyfi](/Aberdyfi) gathering of Welsh princes in 1216. A moment of unity, certainly, but history rarely allows such things to last.

The fragile peace was, of course, temporary. In 1277, the [Treaty of Aberconwy](/Treaty_of_Aberconwy) was signed between [Edward I of England](/Edward_I_of_England) and Llywelyn's grandson, [Llywelyn ap Gruffudd](/Llywelyn_ap_Gruffudd). This agreement, ostensibly granting peace, also carried the rather significant caveat that Welsh self-rule would dissolve upon Llywelyn's death. It was, in essence, the formal completion of the first stage of the [conquest of Wales by Edward I](/Conquest_of_Wales_by_Edward_I)—a meticulously planned, if somewhat tedious, campaign.

Welsh tradition, ever keen on a good origin story, credited the founding of Gwynedd to the Brittonic polity of [Gododdin](/Gododdin) (known in [Old Welsh](/Old_Welsh) as Guotodin, and earlier in its [Brittonic](/Common_Brittonic) form as Votadini) from [Lothian](/Lothian). This narrative suggests an invasion in the 5th century, displacing or absorbing the existing [Brittonic](/Celtic_Britons) polities of the [Deceangli](/Deceangli), [Ordovices](/Ordovices), and [Gangani](/Gangani_(Ireland)). The sons of their legendary leader, [Cunedda](/Cunedda), were then said to have taken possession of the lands between the significant rivers [Dee](/River_Dee,_Wales) and [Teifi](/River_Teifi). While the true borders of this evolving realm were, as one might expect, rather fluid over time, Gwynedd proper was generally considered to encompass the [cantrefs](/Cantref) of [Aberffraw](/Aberffraw_cantref), [Cemais](/Cemais_(Anglesey)), and [Cantref Rhosyr](/Rhosyr_(cantref)) on the island of [Anglesey](/Anglesey). On the mainland, facing the island across the [Menai Strait](/Menai_Strait), it included [Arllechwedd](/Arllechwedd), [Arfon](/Cantref_Arfon), [Dunoding](/Dunoding), [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd), [Llŷn](/Cantref_Ll%C5%B7n), [Rhos](/Rhos_(North_Wales)), [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog), and [Tegeingl](/Tegeingl), all nestled within the formidable, and undeniably beautiful, mountainous region of [Snowdonia](/Snowdonia).

