## Etymology

The name Gwynedd, a name that has endured despite the shifting sands of political power, is generally believed to be a linguistic borrowing from early Irish. This reflects a period of significant Irish settlement in the area during antiquity. It is theorised that the name is either cognate with the [Old Irish](/Old_Irish) ethnic designation *Féni*, referring to the 'Irish people', which itself derives from [Primitive Irish](/Primitive_Irish) `*weidh-n-`, meaning 'forest people' or 'wild people' (ultimately from the [Proto-Indo-European language](/Proto-Indo-European_language) root `*weydʰ-`, 'wood, wilderness'). Alternatively, it could stem from [Old Irish](/Old_Irish) *fían*, signifying a 'war band', which traces back to [Proto-Celtic](/Proto-Celtic_language) `*weinā` (from Proto-Indo-European `*weyh₁-`, 'chase, pursue, suppress'). &#91;20&#93; &#91;21&#93; &#91;22&#93; &#91;23&#93; Either way, it speaks of a frontier, of wildness, and of people who knew how to fight.

The ancient geographer [Ptolemy](/Ptolemy), in the 1st century, rather helpfully marked the [Llŷn Peninsula](/Ll%C5%B7n_Peninsula) as the "Promontory of the [Gangani](/Gangani_(Ireland))". This is a name he also recorded in Ireland, suggesting a clear connection across the Irish Sea. It is theorised that sometime in the 1st century BC, a contingent of the [Gangani](/Gangani_(Ireland)) tribe may have landed in what is now the [Llŷn Peninsula](/Ll%C5%B7n_Peninsula), subsequently driving out the existing [Deceangli](/Deceangli) or [Ordovices](/Ordovices) tribes from that region, whether through peaceful assimilation or, more likely given the era, by force. Later, in the late and post-Roman eras, Irish settlers, potentially from [Leinster](/Leinster) &#91;17&#93;, arrived in [Anglesey](/Anglesey) and other parts of northwest [Wales](/Wales). The name Llŷn itself is believed to be derived from *Laigin*, an [Old Irish](/Old_Irish) form that simply means 'Leinstermen', or more broadly, '[Leinster](/Leinster)'. &#91;25&#93; The ebb and flow of peoples across the Irish Sea was a constant, defining feature of this region, a testament to the fact that borders are often more theoretical than actual.

The earliest tangible record of the name Gwynedd appears to be the 5th-century [Cantiorix Inscription](/Cantiorix_Inscription), now rather prosaically located in [Penmachno](/Penmachno) church. &#91;17&#93; This inscription commemorates a man named Cantiorix, and its [Latin](/Latin) text reads: "Cantiorix hic iacit / Venedotis cives fuit / consobrinos Magli magistrati," which translates to: "Cantiorix lies here. He was a citizen of Gwynedd and a cousin of Maglos the magistrate." &#91;17&#93; The use of terms like "citizen" (*cives*) and "magistrate" (*magistrati*) is often cited as evidence that [Romano-British culture](/Romano-British_culture) and its associated institutions, or at least the terminology, managed to persist in Gwynedd long after the Roman legions had made their rather undignified withdrawal. &#91;17&#93; One might almost imagine a bureaucratic ghost lingering, clinging to titles even as the empire itself crumbled.

## History, background and familial descent

To truly grasp the [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd), one must first endure a brief, but necessary, excursion into the broader [history of Wales](/History_of_Wales) itself. After the last ice age, the lands that would become [Wales](/Wales) were, predictably, settled during [prehistoric](/Prehistoric_Wales) times. &#91;26&#93; [Neolithic](/Neolithic) sites, those enduring markers of early human endeavor, have been unearthed, revealing [tools](/Stone_tool) meticulously crafted from [flint](/Flint). A prime example lies near [Llanfaethlu](/Llanfaethlu), where a [long house](/Neolithic_long_house), a structure dating back 6000 years, has been excavated. &#91;27&#93; &#91;28&#93; Further evidence of this persistent human activity within the regions of Gwynedd and [Anglesey](/Anglesey) can be found at sites such as [Bryn Celli Ddu](/Bryn_Celli_Ddu) on [Anglesey](/Anglesey), a remarkable passage tomb that was constructed in multiple phases, beginning an astonishing 5000 years ago. &#91;29&#93;

[Archaeological](/Archaeological) discoveries from the [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age), stretching back millennia, include significant findings like the [Arthog cauldron](/Nannau,_Wales). This bronze cauldron, dating from around 1100 BC, was discovered near the Merioneth border and is also known, rather poetically, as 'The [Nannau](/Nannau,_Wales) Bucket' (bearing a striking resemblance to the [Dowris bucket](/Dowris_Hoard)). Another ancient artifact is the [Moel Hebog](/Moel_Hebog) shield, also approximately 3,000 years old (and similar to the [Rhyd-y-gors](/Rhyd-y-gors) example). More recently, the [Trawsfynydd](/Trawsfynydd) tankard, a vessel used for the consumption of mead and beer, dates from between 100 BC and 75 AD, offering a glimpse into the more convivial, if still ancient, aspects of life. &#91;30&#93; &#91;31&#93; One wonders if the hangovers were equally timeless.

[Bryn Eryr](/Bryn_Eryr), recreation of pre Roman roundhouse, it's a 2,000-year-old Celtic Iron Age home. &#91;32&#93;

Examples of early settlement in Gwynedd include the reconstructed [Bryn Eryr](/Bryn_Eryr) near [Llansadwrn, Anglesey](/Llansadwrn,_Anglesey), which now resides, somewhat ironically, at the [St Fagans National Museum of History](/St_Fagans_National_Museum_of_History). &#91;33&#93; Another notable site is [Garn Boduan](/Garn_Boduan), a formidable [Celtic](/Celts) [hillfort](/Hillfort) situated on the [Llŷn Peninsula](/Ll%C5%B7n_Peninsula). These [Iron Age](/Iron_Age) forts, these enduring bastions of human defense, were not merely static structures; they were continually adapted and utilized, some even after the initial [Roman conquest of Britain](/Roman_conquest_of_Britain). 'Castle of Buan' (Garn Boduan) in Llŷn, for example, was recorded as being fortified until the 7th century, a testament to its strategic importance and the persistent need for defense. &#91;35&#93; &#91;36&#93;

During the [Roman period](/Wales_in_the_Roman_era), the conquerors, ever keen on infrastructure, constructed new roads and forts throughout their vast empire, and for centuries in [Wales](/Wales) and [England](/Kingdom_of_England). Welsh examples of this Roman imposition include [Caer Gybi (fort)](/Caer_Gybi_(fort)) on [Anglesey](/Anglesey), and [Segontium](/Segontium) in [Caernarfon](/Caernarfon), within Gwynedd itself. &#91;37&#93; &#91;38&#93; The establishment of [Christianity in Wales](/Christianity_in_Wales) also ushered in a new era, as the Romans, in their methodical way, founded towns complete with churches and installed their own [governors](/Roman_governor). However, as the centuries of [sub-Roman Britain](/Sub-Roman_Britain) unfolded, and the imperial grip loosened, new political structures, often less grand but more resilient, began to emerge. It was within this turbulent landscape that the Brythonic [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd) was established in the 5th century. It proved to be the most durable of these nascent Brythonic states, remarkably surviving until the late 13th century, a longevity that few of its contemporaries could boast. &#91;11&#93;

The boundaries and names that emerged from the 1st millennium AD onwards, often forged in conflict and compromise, are, rather stubbornly, still used today to define the towns and counties of the region. &#91;40&#93; The familial descent from the [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd) is, as one might expect, a complex and sprawling affair, encompassing figures of significant historical import. Noteworthy descendants include royalty such as the legendary [Owain Glyndŵr](/Owain_Glynd%C5%B5r) &#91;41&#93; &#91;42&#93;, and, rather ironically given the ultimate fate of Gwynedd, the titular [Prince of Wales](/Prince_of_Wales) &#91;43&#99; &#91;44&#93;. Even the [Salusbury family](/Salusbury_family), through the remarkable [Katheryn of Berain](/Katheryn_of_Berain), lays claim to this lineage. &#91;45&#93;

These influential individuals can often be associated with the [Anglesey](/Anglesey)-based [Tudors of Penmynydd](/Tudors_of_Penmynydd) family. This particular branch of the [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) were, in fact, the direct ancestors and namesake to the former English Royal [House of Tudor](/House_of_Tudor), a dynasty that would leave an indelible mark on British history. Their lineage traces back to the Welshman [Maredudd ap Tudur](/Maredudd_ap_Tudur) &#91;44&#93;, whose own famous ancestor was [Ednyfed Fychan](/Ednyfed_Fychan), a prominent [seneschal](/Seneschal) to the Kings of Gwynedd, demonstrating the enduring influence of administrative power. &#91;46&#93; The [Tudor dynasty](/House_of_Tudor) itself became ancestors to the [House of Stuart](/House_of_Stuart), and the [Stuarts](/House_of_Stuart) subsequently formed the European [Jacobite family](/Jacobite_succession). This intricate web of descent includes direct descendants in the [United Kingdom](/Mountbatten-Windsor), [Ireland](/King_of_Ireland), [France](/Capetian_dynasty), [Germany](/Duke_of_Bavaria), [Italy](/Duke_of_Modena), and numerous other countries across the continent of [Europe](/Europe), truly stretching around the world. &#91;47&#93; &#91;48&#93; It's a rather exhausting testament to the persistent, often inconvenient, intertwining of royal bloodlines.

## Gwynedd in the Early Middle Ages

### Cunedda and his sons

The region, in its nascent stages, became known as Venedotia in [Latin](/Latin). Initially, this name was somewhat narrowly attributed to a specific Irish colony located on [Anglesey](/Anglesey). However, by the 5th century, its scope had broadened, encompassing Irish settlers across North [Wales](/Wales) as a whole. &#91;49&#93; &#91;50&#93; According to the rather opinionated 9th-century monk and chronicler [Nennius](/Nennius), North [Wales](/Wales) found itself in a rather precarious position, left largely defenceless following the Roman withdrawal. It became, quite predictably, subject to increasing raids by marauders from the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man) and [Ireland](/Ireland). This chaotic situation, Nennius recounts, prompted [Cunedda](/Cunedda), his sons, and their considerable entourage, to migrate in the mid-5th century from [Manaw Gododdin](/Manaw_Gododdin) (an area now known as [Clackmannanshire](/Clackmannanshire) in [Scotland](/Scotland)). Their stated purpose was to settle and defend North [Wales](/Wales) against these relentless raiders, thereby bringing the region back under a semblance of [Romano-British](/Romano-British) control. Whether they were genuinely invited to repel invaders or were, in fact, rather well-organized raiders themselves, remains, with characteristic historical ambiguity, unknown. &#91;17&#93; &#91;51&#93;

Traditional pedigrees, those meticulous records of lineage so crucial in Welsh society, assert that [Cunedda](/Cunedda)'s grandfather was [Padarn Beisrudd](/Padarn_Beisrudd), a name that translates intriguingly as "Paternus of the red cloak." This epithet, as one might infer, "suggests that he wore the cloak of a Roman officer," &#91;17&#93; perhaps even serving as evidence of a high-ranking officer, a lingering echo of imperial authority in a fading world. &#91;51&#93; &#91;b&#93; [Cunedda](/Cunedda) himself (fl. &#8201;5th century) is credited with bringing a much-needed, if temporary, order to [North Wales](/North_Wales). Upon his death, however, Gwynedd was, in a move that would become depressingly familiar, divided among his sons. Dynod was awarded [Dunoding](/Dunoding), another son, [Ceredig](/Ceredig), received [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion), "Afloeg by Aflogion in [Lleyn](/Ll%C5%B7n_Peninsula), Dogfael by [Dogfeiling](/Dogfeiling) in [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd), and Edern by [Edeirnion](/Edeirnion) ... Osfeilion of Osfael has not yet been located; Tybion, the eldest son, is said to have died in Manaw Gododdin, but his son Meirion (Marianus) comes into the picture as lord of [Meirionydd](/Meirionydd). [Einion Yrth](/Einion_Yrth_ap_Cunedda) completes the number." It was [Cadwallon Lawhir ap Einion](/Cadwallon_Lawhir_ap_Einion), one of his grandsons, who is ultimately credited with delivering the final, decisive defeat to the Irish presence on [Anglesey](/Anglesey). &#91;51&#93;

However, this rather neatly packaged origin myth, while convenient for establishing legitimacy, has been met with a healthy dose of skepticism. &#91;c&#93; As one historian rather pointedly observed:
"Early Welsh literature contains a wealth of stories seeking to explain place-names, and doubtless, the story is propaganda aimed at justifying the right of Cunedda and his descendants to territories beyond the borders of the original [Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd). That kingdom probably consisted of the two banks of the [Menai Straits](/Menai_Strait) and the coast over towards the estuary of the [River Conwy](/River_Conwy), the foundations upon which Cunedda's descendants created a more extensive realm." &#91;17&#93;
A rather predictable pattern, wouldn't you say? Power seeks justification, and history is often happy to oblige, with a few convenient embellishments.

Despite the inevitable political machinations, the inhabitants of Gwynedd demonstrably remained conscious of their [Romano-British](/Romano-British) heritage. An affinity with Rome, a phantom limb of empire, survived long after the actual empire retreated from Britain. This was particularly evident in the continued, albeit limited, use of [Latin](/Latin_language) in writing and in the tenacious sustenance of the [Christian religion](/Christianity_in_Wales). The ruling classes, ever pragmatic, continued to emphasize Roman ancestors within their meticulously maintained pedigrees, a clever strategy to link their authority with the old imperial Roman order, thereby suggesting a comforting sense of stability and continuity with a past that was, in reality, rapidly receding. &#91;17&#93; &#91;53&#93; According to Professor [John Davies](/John_Davies_(historian)), there was "a determinedly Brythonic, and indeed Roman, air to early Gwynedd." &#91;17&#93; So palpable was this lingering Roman heritage that Professor [Bryan Ward-Perkins](/Bryan_Ward-Perkins) of [Trinity College, Oxford](/Trinity_College,_Oxford), made a rather striking claim: "it took until 1282, when [Edward I](/Edward_I_of_England) conquered [Gwynedd](/Gwynedd), for the last part of Roman Britain to fall [and] a strong case can be made for Gwynedd as the very last part of the entire Roman Empire, east and west, to fall to the [barbarians](/Barbarians)." &#91;53&#93; &#91;d&#93; A grand, if somewhat depressing, epitaph for a stubborn holdout.

Nevertheless, this clinging to Roman identity was largely superficial. There was, in fact, a generally swift abandonment of actual Roman political, social, and ecclesiastical practices and institutions within Gwynedd and, indeed, elsewhere in [Wales](/Wales). Roman knowledge, particularly its more complex forms, was simply lost as the [Romano-Britons](/Romano-British) shifted, out of sheer necessity, towards a streamlined, militaristic, and almost tribal society. This new reality no longer supported, or required, the use of coinage and other complex industries dependent on a money economy, nor the intricate architectural techniques employing brick and mortar. Even more basic knowledge, such as the efficient use of the wheel in pottery production, faded away. &#91;53&#93; Ward-Perkins suggests that the Welsh were compelled to abandon those Roman ways that proved either insufficient or, more pointedly, superfluous, to meet the existential challenge of survival they faced. "Militarized tribal societies, despite their political fragmentation and internecine strife, seem to have offered better protection against Germanic invasion than exclusive dependence on a professional Roman army (that in the troubled years of the fifth century was all too prone to melt away or mutiny)." &#91;53&#93;

Reverting to a more militaristic tribal society, while perhaps appearing a step backward to some, allowed the Welsh of Gwynedd to concentrate their energies on the martial skills absolutely necessary for their very survival. The [Romano-Britons](/Romano-British) of western Britain, adopting this brutal pragmatism, offered stiffer and, in the end, ultimately successful resistance against the encroaching Anglo-Saxons. &#91;53&#93; The region of Venedotia, however, had a unique vulnerability. Having been under direct Roman military administration, and already hosting established [Gaelic](/Gaels) settlements, its civilian element was less extensive and deeply rooted. This pre-existing condition may have, rather conveniently for the forces of change, facilitated a more rapid and widespread technological loss than in other areas. &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)

### Kingdom of Gwynedd c. 620

In the tumultuous post-Roman period, the earliest rulers of [Wales](/Wales) and Gwynedd likely exerted authority over territories no larger than the [cantrefi](/Cantref), those administrative units roughly comparable to the [hundreds](/Hundred_(county_division)) described in [Welsh law](/Welsh_law) centuries later. Their size, in a practical sense, was somewhat analogous to the Irish [tuath](/Tuath). These early petty kings or princelings (Lloyd, in a moment of perhaps unwarranted generosity, used the term "chieftain") adopted the title *rhi* in Welsh, akin to the Irish Gaelic *[rí](/R%C3%AD)*. This title was later, and perhaps more grandly, replaced by *brenin*, a term used to "denote a less archaic form of [kingship](/Monarch)," according to Professor [John Davies](/John_Davies_(historian)).

Genealogical lists, compiled around 960, meticulously bear out that a number of these early rulers, ever keen on legitimacy, claimed degrees of association with the old Roman order. However, rather inconveniently for their claims, they do not appear in the official royal lineages. "It may be assumed that the stronger kings annexed the territories of their weaker neighbours and that the lineages of the victors are the only lineages to have survived," Davies concluded, with a touch of weary realism. Smaller, weaker chieftains, with predictable self-interest, coalesced around more powerful princelings, sometimes through voluntary vassalage or inheritance, though, at other times, through less voluntary conquest. These lesser princelings, in turn, coalesced around still greater princelings, until a regional prince could, for a brief, shining moment, claim authority over the whole of north [Wales](/Wales), stretching from the [River Dyfi](/River_Dovey) in the south to the [Dee](/River_Dee,_Wales) in the east, and encompassing the strategically vital [Anglesey](/Anglesey). &#91;17&#93; &#91;page needed](/Wikipedia:Citing_sources) It's a rather predictable pattern of consolidation, isn't it?

Other evidence, perhaps less romanticized than Nennius's account, supports his claim that a leader did indeed come to [North Wales](/North_Wales) and, for a time, brought the region a measure of much-needed stability &#91;55&#93;. This was despite a persistent Irish Gaelic element that remained active until the mid-5th century. [Cunedda](/Cunedda)'s heir, [Einion Yrth ap Cunedda](/Einion_Yrth_ap_Cunedda), is credited with decisively defeating the remaining Gaelic Irish on [Anglesey](/Anglesey) by 470. His son, [Cadwallon Lawhir ap Einion](/Cadwallon_Lawhir_ap_Einion), appears to have further consolidated the realm during a period of relative peace that followed the pivotal [Battle of Badon](/Battle_of_Badon), where the Anglo-Saxons suffered a significant, if temporary, setback. During this lull, he established what was, for the time, a mighty kingdom. After [Cadwallon](/Cadwallon_Lawhir_ap_Einion), Gwynedd seems to have held a pre-eminent position among the various petty Cambrian states of the post-Roman period. &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed)

The great-grandson of [Cunedda](/Cunedda), [Maelgwn Hir](/Maelgwn_Gwynedd) (Maelgwn the Tall), &#91;51&#93; &#91;56&#93; was, by all accounts, an able military leader – impetuous when it suited him, and generous when it served his interests. &#91;57&#93; His life, as is often the case with such figures, is shrouded in a mist of legend, featuring tales of his own trickery and craftiness &#91;58&#93;, or, conversely, accounts of miracles performed against him by various Christian saints. &#91;59&#93; He is even attributed, in some old stories, as hosting the very first [Eisteddfod](/Eisteddfod), a rather grand cultural legacy. &#91;60&#93; However, he is perhaps most famously known as one of five Celtic British kings rather scathingly castigated for their sins by the contemporary Christian writer [Gildas](/Gildas). Gildas, with his usual lack of subtlety, referred to him as Maglocunus, meaning 'Prince-Hound' in Brittonic, and curiously described him as "the dragon of the island"—possibly a title, but explicitly as the most powerful of the five named British kings. Gildas's assessment, delivered with characteristic fire and brimstone, stated: "[Y]ou the last I write of but the first and greatest in evil, more than many in ability but also in malice, more generous in giving but also more liberal in sin, strong in war but stronger to destroy your soul." &#91;62&#93; A rather ringing endorsement, if you consider the source.

[Maelgwn](/Maelgwn_Gwynedd) eventually succumbed to the plague in 547 &#91;57&#93;, leaving, as powerful rulers often do, a rather messy succession crisis in his wake. His son-in-law, [Elidyr Mwynfawr](/Kingdom_of_Strathclyde) of the [Kingdom of Strathclyde](/Kingdom_of_Strathclyde), swiftly laid claim to the throne, launching an invasion of Gwynedd in a rather direct attempt to displace Maelgwn's son, [Rhun Hir ap Maelgwn](/Rhun_Hir_ap_Maelgwn). Elidyr, however, was killed in the attempt &#91;63&#93;, a predictable outcome for such brazen ambition. His death was, of course, avenged by his relatives, who proceeded to ravage the coast of [Arfon](/District_of_Arfon). [Rhun](/Rhun_Hir_ap_Maelgwn) counter-attacked, exacting the same brutal penalty on the lands of his foes in what is now South and Central [Scotland](/Scotland). &#91;64&#93; The sheer distances covered by these armies suggest either a rather extensive network of alliances, or, more likely, travel across the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea). However, given that almost all of what is now northern [England](/Kingdom_of_England) was, at this point (c. 550), under Brittonic rule, it is entirely possible that his army marched to [Strathclyde](/Kingdom_of_Strathclyde) overland. [Rhun](/Rhun_Hir_ap_Maelgwn) eventually returned to Gwynedd, and the remainder of his reign was, for the most part, uneventful, until Elidir's relatives, with predictable persistence, renewed their aggressions, leading to Rhun's death in the ensuing conflict. &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) He was succeeded by his son, or in some accounts, his nephew, [Beli ap Rhun](/Beli_ap_Rhun), around 586. &#91;65&#93;

Upon the accession of Beli's son, [Iago ap Beli](/Iago_ap_Beli), around 599, the situation in Britain had, to put it mildly, deteriorated significantly. Most of northern [England](/Kingdom_of_England) had been overrun by the invading [Angles](/Angles_(tribe)) of [Deira](/Deira) and [Bernicia](/Bernicia), who were in the process of forming the formidable [Kingdom of Northumbria](/Kingdom_of_Northumbria). In a rare, and perhaps desperate, display of common interest, it appears that Gwynedd and the neighbouring [Kingdom of Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) acted in concert to rebuff the relentless Anglian advance. Their efforts, however, were ultimately defeated at the devastating [Battle of Chester](/Battle_of_Chester) in 613. Following this catastrophe, the approximate borders of northern [Wales](/Wales) were, with grim finality, set, with the city of Caerlleon (now known as [Chester](/Chester)) and the surrounding [Cheshire Plain](/Cheshire_Plain) falling firmly under the control of the Anglo-Saxons. &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) Beli's grandson was [Cadfan ap Iago](/Cadfan_ap_Iago), a direct descendant from the line of [Maelgwn](/Maelgwn_Gwynedd). His tombstone in Gwynedd, inscribed in [Latin](/Latin_language), proudly declared him "Catamanus rex sapientisimus opinatisimus" (most renowned), a fitting epitaph for an ancestor of the future Kings of Gwynedd. &#91;66&#93; &#91;67&#93;

### Cadwallon ap Cadfan

Gravestone of [Cadfan ap Iago](/Cadfan_ap_Iago), father of [Cadwallon ap Cadfan](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan)

The [Battle of Chester](/Battle_of_Chester), despite its devastating outcome for the Welsh, did not, by any means, extinguish their ability to seriously threaten the burgeoning Anglo-Saxon polities. &#91;68&#93; Among the most powerful, and certainly the most tenacious, of the early kings was [Cadwallon ap Cadfan](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan) (c. 624 – 634) &#91;69&#93; &#91;70&#93;, grandson of [Iago ap Beli](/Iago_ap_Beli). He embarked upon an initially disastrous campaign against [Northumbria](/Kingdom_of_Northumbria), suffering a series of epic defeats that saw him confined first to [Anglesey](/Anglesey) &#91;71&#93;, and then, rather ignominiously, to just [Puffin Island](/Puffin_Island_(Anglesey)) &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed). Ultimately, he was forced into exile across the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea) to [Dublin](/Dublin), a city that would, with depressing regularity, come to host many royal refugees from Gwynedd. All, it seemed, must have been lost.

But [Cadwallon](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan) (known in [Welsh](/Welsh_language) as Meigen), with a resilience that bordered on the miraculous, managed to raise an enormous army. After a brief sojourn in [Guernsey](/Guernsey), he invaded [Dumnonia](/Dumnonia), providing much-needed relief to the [West Welsh](/Cornish_people) who were suffering under a Mercian invasion. He then, with a stroke of strategic genius, forced the pagan [Penda of Mercia](/Penda_of_Mercia) into an unlikely alliance against their common enemy, [Northumbria](/Northumbria). &#91;citation needed](/Wikipedia:Citation_needed) With renewed vigour, [Cadwallon](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan) returned to face his Northumbrian foes, decisively defeating their armies and, in a brutal display of power, slaying a succession of their kings. In this furious campaign, his armies devastated [Northumbria](/Northumbria), culminating in the capture and sacking of [York](/York) in 633, and a brief, but significant, control over the kingdom. &#91;71&#93; It was during this period that, according to the venerable [Bede](/Bede), many Northumbrians were slaughtered "with savage cruelty" by [Cadwallon](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan). &#91;72&#93;

•
[H]e neither spared the female sex, nor the innocent age of children, but with savage cruelty put them to tormenting deaths, ravaging all their country for a long time, and resolving to cut off all the race of the English within the borders of Britain.

—&#8202;[Bede](/Bede), [Ecclesiastical History of the English People](/Ecclesiastical_History_of_the_English_People) &#91;73&#93;

Despite the relentless warfare and the 14 battles undertaken by the allied forces of Gwynedd and Mercia against Northumbria, the chief among them being the [Battle of Cefn Digoll](/Battle_of_Cefn_Digoll) in 632, a strategic alliance was eventually concluded when [Cadwallon](/Cadwallon_ap_Cadfan) married Alcfritha, the daughter of [Pybba of Mercia](/Pybba_of_Mercia). However, the profound effect of these tumultuous events would, as is often the case with such fleeting victories, prove to be short-lived. He met his end in battle in 634, tragically close to [Hadrian's Wall](/Hadrian%27s_Wall), at the infamous [Battle of Heavenfield](/Battle_of_Heavenfield). &#91;71&#93; &#91;69&#93; On account of these audacious deeds, he and his son [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr), who later fought at the brutal [Battle of the Winwaed](/Battle_of_the_Winwaed) &#91;74&#93;, appear to have been considered the last two [High Kings of Britain](/List_of_legendary_kings_of_Britain), a grand title for a lineage that was about to shift. [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr) himself presided over a period of consolidation, dedicating much of his time and resources to the Church, an endeavor that earned him the revered title "Bendigaid," meaning "Blessed." In his later life, he embraced the monastic path, becoming involved with [Clynnog's abbey](/Clynnog_fawr), and his legacy is still honoured at [St Cadwaladr's Church, Llangadwaladr](/St_Cadwaladr%27s_Church,_Llangadwaladr) on [Anglesey](/Anglesey). &#91;75&#93; The [Tudors of Penmynydd](/Tudors_of_Penmynydd) and, most notably, [Henry VII of England](/Henry_VII_of_England), would later rather proudly claim direct descent from Cadwaladr, asserting their lineage "in the twenty-second degree." &#91;76&#93; &#91;74&#93; &#91;77&#93; &#91;e&#93; A convenient claim, to be sure, linking new power to ancient, hallowed lines.

### Rhodri the Great and Aberffraw primacy

During the latter part of the 9th and 10th centuries, the coastal areas of Gwynedd, particularly the strategically vital [Anglesey](/Anglesey), found themselves under increasing and rather unwelcome attack by the [Vikings](/Vikings). As if external threats weren't enough, [Wales](/Wales) had also been embroiled in ongoing conflicts with the neighbouring English Kingdoms of [Mercia](/Mercia) and [Wessex](/Wessex), who, in a rather opportunistic move, were often assisted by [Anglo-Saxons](/Anglo-Saxons) and [Danes](/Danes) (Vikings). However, it was, rather ironically, the kings of Welsh kingdoms who were sometimes protected by these very [Scandinavian York](/Scandinavian_York) mercenaries. &#91;78&#93; &#91;79&#93; These relentless raids, no doubt, had a seriously debilitating effect on the country, disrupting trade, causing widespread destruction, and fostering a pervasive sense of insecurity. Fortunately for Gwynedd, the victims of the Vikings were not confined to [Wales](/Wales); their destructive appetites were far-reaching.

The [House of Cunedda](/List_of_rulers_of_Gwynedd), as the direct descendants of the legendary [Cunedda](/Cunedda) are known, eventually expired in the male line in 825 upon the death of [Hywel ap Rhodri Molwynog](/Hywel_ap_Rhodri_Molwynog). As the historian [John Edward Lloyd](/John_Edward_Lloyd) rather dryly put it, "a stranger possessed the throne of Gwynedd." &#91;80&#93; A dramatic turn, if one were prone to such things.

[Kingdom of Gwynedd](/Kingdom_of_Gwynedd) c. 830

This "stranger" who ascended to the throne of Gwynedd was [Merfyn "Frych"](/Merfyn_Frych) (Merfyn "the Freckled"). &#91;81&#93; When, however, one bothers to examine [Merfyn Frych](/Merfyn_Frych)'s pedigree – and to the Welsh, pedigree meant absolutely everything, a meticulous accounting of every ancestor – he seems not a stranger at all, but rather a direct descendant of the ancient ruling line, albeit through a female line. He was the son of Gwriad, the contemporaneous [King of Mann](/King_of_Mann) from the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man), and, depending on the historical source, either the son or husband of Essyllt, daughter of Cynan Dindaethwy, a former King of Gwynedd. The most ancient genealogical sources, with their usual meticulousness, agree that Merfyn was the son of Essyllt &#91;82&#93;, who was both heiress and cousin of the aforementioned [Hywel ap Caradog](/Hywel_ap_Caradog), the last of the ruling [House of Cunedda](/List_of_rulers_of_Gwynedd) in Gwynedd. Furthermore, Merfyn's male line traced back to the [Hen Ogledd](/Hen_Ogledd) (the Old North) to [Llywarch Hen](/Llywarch_Hen) &#91;81&#93;, a first cousin of [Urien](/Urien) and thus a direct descendant of [Coel Hen](/Coel_Hen). Thus, the [House of Cunedda](/List_of_rulers_of_Gwynedd) and the newly emerging [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw), as Merfyn's descendants would come to be known, shared [Coel Hen](/Coel_Hen) as a common ancestor, though the [House of Cunedda](/List_of_rulers_of_Gwynedd) traced their line through Gwawl, his daughter and wife of [Cunedda](/Cunedda). &#91;83&#93; The web of lineage, as always, proved to be far more intricate than a simple glance might suggest.

[Merfyn](/Merfyn_Frych) married [Nest ferch Cadell](/Nest_ferch_Cadell), the sister or daughter of [Cyngen ap Cadell](/Cyngen_ap_Cadell), the King of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) from the [Gwertherion dynasty](/List_of_rulers_of_Wales), thereby strategically solidifying his position. He then founded the [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw), named after his principal court on [Anglesey](/Anglesey), a move that firmly established a new power center. &#91;84&#93; &#91;85&#93; Unfortunately, no written records are preserved from the Britons of southern [Scotland](/Scotland) and northern [England](/Kingdom_of_England) during this period. However, it is highly probable that [Merfyn Frych](/Merfyn_Frych) brought many of these northern legends, along with his carefully preserved pedigree, with him when he arrived in north [Wales](/Wales). It appears most probable that it was at Merfyn's court, and subsequently that of his son, that all the rich lore of the north was diligently collected and committed to writing, ensuring its survival. &#91;86&#93; A pragmatic approach to cultural preservation, one might say.

[Rhodri the Great](/Rhodri_the_Great) (844–878), the formidable son of [Merfyn Frych](/Merfyn_Frych) and [Nest ferch Cadell](/Nest_ferch_Cadell) &#91;87&#93;, proved to be a master of expansion. He was able to add the [Kingdom of Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) to his already growing realm after its king, his maternal uncle, died on a pilgrimage to [Rome](/Rome) in 855. Later, he further cemented his power through marriage, taking [Angharad ferch Meurig](/Angharad_ferch_Meurig), the sister of King [Gwgon](/Gwgon) of [Seisyllwg](/Seisyllwg), as his wife. When Gwgon, rather inconveniently, drowned without an heir in 872, [Rhodri](/Rhodri_the_Great) swiftly became a steward over the kingdom, and, with characteristic efficiency, installed his son, [Cadell ap Rhodri](/Cadell_ap_Rhodri), as a subject king. Thus, [Rhodri](/Rhodri_the_Great) became the first ruler since the legendary days of [Cunedda](/Cunedda) to control the greater part of [Wales](/Wales), a truly remarkable, if fleeting, achievement. &#91;88&#93; &#91;89&#93;

When [Rhodri](/Rhodri_the_Great) died in 878 [AD](/AD), reportedly in battle against [Ceolwulf I of Mercia](/Ceolwulf_I_of_Mercia) &#91;79&#93;, the relative unity he had forged in [Wales](/Wales) predictably fractured. The realm was once again divided into its constituent parts, each ruled by one of his sons. [Rhodri](/Rhodri_the_Great)'s eldest son, [Anarawd ap Rhodri](/Anarawd_ap_Rhodri), inherited Gwynedd and would firmly establish the princely [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw), ensuring its continued prominence. His son, [Merfyn ap Rhodri](/Merfyn_ap_Rhodri), was given the [Kingdom of Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) to rule, while [Cadell](/Cadell_ap_Rhodri) founded the medieval Welsh Royal [House of Dinefwr](/House_of_Dinefwr) in [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth). This division effectively delineated [North Wales](/North_Wales), [Mid Wales](/Mid_Wales), and [South Wales](/South_Wales) respectively. Gwynedd and the [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) [dynasty](/Dynasty) continued to thrive, with only a few interruptions, until the ultimate conquest in 1283. &#91;88&#93; &#91;89&#93; &#91;90&#93;

From the considerable successes of [Rhodri](/Rhodri_the_Great) and the seniority of [Anarawd](/Anarawd_ap_Rhodri) among his sons, the [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) family rather confidently claimed primacy over all other Welsh lords. This included even the powerful kings of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) and [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth), a bold assertion of their pre-eminence. &#91;91&#93; &#91;92&#93; &#91;f&#93; In *The History of [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)*, a significant biographical work written in the late 12th century &#91;93&#93; &#91;94&#93;, the family meticulously asserted its rights as the senior line of descendants from [Rhodri the Great](/Rhodri_the_Great), who had, after all, conquered most of [Wales](/Wales) during his lifetime. [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s biography was notably first written in [Latin](/Latin), a clear indication that it was intended for a wider, European audience beyond the immediate Welsh borders. The profound significance of this claim was that the [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) family, unlike many other lesser lords, owed absolutely nothing to the English king for its position in [Wales](/Wales). They held authority in [Wales](/Wales) "by absolute right through descent," as historian [John Davies](/John_Davies_(historian)) so succinctly put it. &#91;91&#93; A powerful, if ultimately insufficient, argument against encroaching empires.

The [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) was, for a time, displaced in 942 by [Hywel Dda](/Hywel_Dda), a King of [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth) who stemmed from a junior line of descent from [Rhodri Mawr](/Rhodri_the_Great). &#91;95&#93; &#91;96&#93; This unfortunate turn of events occurred because [Idwal Foel](/Idwal_Foel) &#91;97&#93;, the reigning King of Gwynedd, with a perhaps ill-advised determination, resolved to cast off English overlordship and took up arms against the new English king, [Edmund I](/Edmund_I). Both Idwal and his brother Elisedd were tragically killed in battle against Edmund's forces. &#91;98&#93; By normal custom, Idwal's crown should have passed to his sons, [Ieuaf](/Ieuaf) and [Iago ab Idwal](/Iago_ab_Idwal). However, [Hywel Dda](/Hywel_Dda), ever the opportunist, intervened, sending Iago and Ieuaf into exile in [Ireland](/Ireland) and establishing himself as ruler over Gwynedd until his death in 950. Only then was the [House of Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) restored to its rightful, if temporarily interrupted, position. Nonetheless, surviving manuscripts of [Cyfraith Hywel](/Cyfraith_Hywel), the ancient Welsh laws, rather diplomatically recognise the importance of the lords of [Aberffraw](/Aberffraw) as overlords of [Wales](/Wales) alongside the [rulers of Deheubarth](/Rulers_of_Deheubarth). &#91;99&#93; &#91;g&#93; A careful balancing act, even in legal texts.

Between 986 and 1081, the throne of Gwynedd was, with a frequency that suggests chronic instability, often in contention. The rightful kings were frequently displaced by rivals, both from within and outside the realm, a predictable pattern in a fractured political landscape. One such ambitious figure was [Gruffudd ap Llywelyn](/Gruffudd_ap_Llywelyn), originally from [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys). He successfully displaced the [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) line from Gwynedd, establishing himself as ruler there, and by 1055, had managed to make himself king of most of [Wales](/Wales), a truly impressive, if fleeting, consolidation of power. &#91;100&#93; He became powerful enough to present a genuine menace to [England](/Kingdom_of_England), even annexing some neighbouring parts after a series of victories over English armies. Eventually, however, he was defeated by [Harold Godwinson](/Harold_Godwinson) in 1063 and, in a rather brutal turn of events, later killed by his own men in a deal designed to secure peace with [England](/Kingdom_of_England). &#91;101&#93; [Bleddyn ap Cynfyn](/Bleddyn_ap_Cynfyn) and his brother Rhiwallon, of the [Mathrafal](/House_of_Mathrafal) dynasty of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys), and Gruffudd's maternal half-brothers, came to terms with Harold and took over the rule of Gwynedd and [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys). &#91;102&#93;

Shortly after the fateful [Norman conquest of England](/Norman_conquest_of_England) in 1066, the Normans, ever expansionist, began to exert increasing pressure on the eastern border of Gwynedd. Their efforts were, rather conveniently, aided by internal strife following the killing of [Bleddyn ap Cynfyn](/Bleddyn_ap_Cynfyn) in 1075 by his second cousin, Rhys ap Owain, King of [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth). &#91;102&#93; Another relative of Bleddyn's, [Trahaearn ap Caradog](/Trahaearn_ap_Caradog), seized the throne, but his reign was predictably short-lived, as he was soon challenged by [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) &#91;103&#93;. Gruffudd, the exiled grandson of [Iago ab Idwal ap Meurig](/Iago_ab_Idwal_ap_Meurig), had been patiently biding his time in the [Norse–Gael](/Norse%E2%80%93Gaels) stronghold of [Dublin](/Dublin). &#91;104&#93; &#91;105&#93; In 1081, [Trahaearn](/Trahaearn_ap_Caradog) was killed by [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) in battle, and with that, the ancient line of [Rhodri Mawr](/Rhodri_the_Great) was, for a time, restored. &#91;103&#93; A familiar narrative arc: exile, return, and bloody vengeance.

## Gwynedd in the High Middle Ages

### Gruffudd ap Cynan

[Wales](/Wales) c. 1063 – 1081

The [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) dynasty, like a recurring bad dream, suffered various [depositions](/Deposition_(politics)) by rivals from [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth), [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys), and [England](/Kingdom_of_England) throughout the 10th and 11th centuries. [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) (c. 1055–1137) &#91;13&#93; &#91;106&#93;, who had the rather formative experience of growing up in exile in [Norse–Gael Dublin](/History_of_Dublin), eventually managed to regain his inheritance following his decisive victory at the [Battle of Mynydd Carn](/Battle_of_Mynydd_Carn) in 1081. This victory was over his [Mathrafal](/House_of_Mathrafal) rivals who, in his absence, had rather inconveniently taken control of Gwynedd. &#91;107&#93; &#91;108&#93;

However, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s moment of triumph was, predictably, short-lived. The [Normans](/Normans), fresh from their conquest of [England](/Kingdom_of_England), launched a comprehensive invasion of [Wales](/Wales) in the wake of the Saxon revolt in [northern England](/Northern_England), an event grimly remembered as the [Harrying of the North](/Harrying_of_the_North). &#91;109&#93;

Shortly after the [Battle of Mynydd Carn](/Battle_of_Mynydd_Carn) in 1081, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) was, rather foolishly, lured into a trap with the deceptive promise of an alliance. He was promptly seized by [Hugh d'Avranches, Earl of Chester](/Hugh_d%27Avranches,_Earl_of_Chester), in an ambush near [Corwen](/Corwen). &#91;108&#93; &#91;110&#93; Earl Hugh, with characteristic Norman ambition, claimed the Perfeddwlad (the 'Middle Country') right up to the [River Clwyd](/River_Clwyd). This encompassed the [commotes](/Commote) of [Tegeingl](/Tegeingl) and [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog), corresponding to the modern counties of [Denbighshire](/Denbighshire), Flintshire, and [Wrexham](/Wrexham), as part of his expanding Chester territory. The restoration of the [Aberffraw](/House_of_Aberffraw) family in Gwynedd was, quite rightly, perceived as a direct threat to his own aggressive expansion into [Wales](/Wales). The lands west of the [Clwyd](/River_Clwyd) were earmarked for his cousin, [Robert of Rhuddlan](/Robert_of_Rhuddlan), and their relentless advance had, by 1090, extended all the way to the [Llŷn Peninsula](/Ll%C5%B7n_Peninsula). By 1094, almost the entire country of [Wales](/Wales) found itself under a rather tenuous [occupation](/Military_occupation) by Norman forces. However, despite the erection of numerous imposing castles, Norman control in most regions of [Wales](/Wales) was, at best, precarious. Motivated by widespread local anger over the "gratuitously cruel" invaders, and galvanized by their historic ruling houses, Welsh control over the greater part of [Wales](/Wales) was, with impressive speed, restored by 1100. &#91;108&#93;

In a further effort to consolidate his precarious control over Gwynedd, Earl Hugh of Chester, in a move typical of the era, had [Hervey le Breton](/Hervey_le_Breton) elected as [Bishop of Bangor](/Bishop_of_Bangor) in 1092. Hervey was then duly [consecrated](/Consecrated) by [Thomas of Bayeux](/Thomas_of_Bayeux), the [Archbishop of York](/Archbishop_of_York). &#91;111&#93; &#91;h&#93; This was a calculated attempt to assert Norman authority over the traditionally independent Welsh church. However, the Welsh [parishioners](/Parishioner) remained, with characteristic stubbornness, deeply hostile to Hervey's appointment. The bishop was, rather comically, forced to carry a sword with him at all times and rely on a contingent of Norman knights for his personal protection. &#91;113&#93; &#91;114&#93; Furthermore, Hervey, with an evident lack of subtlety, routinely [excommunicated](/Excommunicated) any parishioners who dared to challenge his spiritual and temporal authority. &#91;113&#93; One imagines this did little to endear him to the local populace.

[Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) escapes from Chester. Illustration by T. Prytherch in 1900

[Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), with a flair for the dramatic, eventually escaped his imprisonment in Chester and, in a rather satisfying turn of events, slew [Robert of Rhuddlan](/Robert_of_Rhuddlan) in a beachside battle at Deganwy on 3 July 1093. &#91;110&#93; [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) swiftly recovered Gwynedd by 1095, and by 1098, demonstrating a pragmatic ability to set aside old rivalries, he allied with [Cadwgan ap Bleddyn](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) of the [Mathrafal](/House_of_Mathrafal) house of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys), their traditional dynastic animosity notwithstanding. [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) and [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) then proceeded to lead the Welsh resistance against the Norman occupation in north and mid-[Wales](/Wales).

However, by 1098, Earl Hugh of Chester and [Hugh of Montgomery, 2nd Earl of Shrewsbury](/Hugh_of_Montgomery,_2nd_Earl_of_Shrewsbury), advanced their combined army to the [Menai Strait](/Menai_Strait). [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) and [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn), ever resourceful, regrouped on the defensible island of [Anglesey](/Anglesey), where they planned to launch [retaliatory strikes](/Guerrilla_warfare) from their island fortress. [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), in a display of his [Norse–Gael](/Norse%E2%80%93Gaels) connections, hired a Norse fleet from a settlement in [Ireland](/Ireland) to patrol the [Menai](/Menai_Strait) and prevent the Norman army from crossing. However, the Normans, with a predictable lack of scruple, were able to pay off the fleet to instead ferry *them* to Môn. Betrayed and outmaneuvered, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) and [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) were forced to flee to [Ireland](/Ireland) in a [skiff](/Skiff). &#91;107&#93; &#91;108&#93; A rather ignominious, if temporary, retreat.

The Normans, having successfully landed on [Anglesey](/Anglesey), celebrated their 'victory' with a fury that was exceptionally violent. Rape and carnage were committed by the Norman army, left unchecked by their commanders. The Earl of Shrewsbury, in a particularly egregious act, had an elderly priest mutilated and, with breathtaking sacrilege, made the church of [Llandyfrydog](/Llandyfrydog) a kennel for his dogs. &#91;107&#93; Such gratuitous cruelty, as history often demonstrates, rarely goes unpunished.

During these brutal 'celebrations', a Norse fleet led by [Magnus Barefoot](/Magnus_Barefoot), the formidable [King of Norway](/Monarchy_of_Norway) &#91;i&#93;, appeared off the coast at [Puffin Island](/Puffin_Island_(Anglesey)). In the ensuing battle, known as the [Battle of Anglesey Sound](/Battle_of_Anglesey_Sound), Magnus, with a precision that bordered on poetic justice, shot dead the Earl of Shrewsbury with an arrow to the eye. The Norse, having delivered their unexpected blow, departed as suddenly and mysteriously as they had arrived, leaving the Norman army significantly weakened and demoralized. &#91;107&#93; A timely intervention, if ever there was one.

The Norman army, its morale shattered and its leadership compromised, retired to [England](/Kingdom_of_England), leaving a Welshman, [Owain ab Edwin of Tegeingl](/Owain_ab_Edwin_of_Tegeingl), in command of a token force to control Ynys Môn (now [Anglesey](/Anglesey)) and upper Gwynedd. This effectively signaled the abandonment of any serious [colonisation](/Colonisation) plans there. &#91;107&#93; &#91;116&#93; [Owain ap Edwin](/Owain_ab_Edwin_of_Tegeingl), ever the pragmatist, had transferred his allegiance to Chester following the defeat of his ally [Trahaearn ap Caradog](/Trahaearn_ap_Caradog) in 1081, a move that rather predictably earned him the epithet *Bradwr* ("the Traitor" in [Welsh](/Welsh_language): Owain Fradwr) among his own people. &#91;116&#93;

In late 1098, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) and [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) landed back in [Wales](/Wales) and, with surprising ease, recovered [Anglesey](/Anglesey). Hervé the Breton, the unpopular Bishop of Bangor, prudently fled Bangor for safety in [England](/Kingdom_of_England). Over the course of the next three years, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) systematically recovered upper Gwynedd, pushing his territory back to the [Conwy](/Conwy), and decisively defeating Hugh, [Earl of Chester](/Earl_of_Chester). In 1101, following Earl Hugh's death, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) and [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) came to terms with [England](/Kingdom_of_England)'s new king, [Henry I](/Henry_I_of_England), who was, predictably, keen on consolidating his own authority and eager for a swift resolution. In the subsequent negotiations, [Henry I](/Henry_I_of_England) formally recognised [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s ancestral claims to [Anglesey](/Anglesey), [Llŷn](/Cantref_Ll%C5%B7n), [Dunoding](/Dunoding) ([Eifionydd](/Eifionydd) and [Ardudwy](/Ardudwy)), and [Arllechwedd](/Arllechwedd), effectively conceding the lands of upper Gwynedd to the [Conwy](/Conwy) which were, in any case, already firmly under [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s control. [Cadwgan](/Cadwgan_ap_Bleddyn) regained [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion) and his share of the family inheritance in [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) from the new Earl of Shrewsbury, [Robert of Bellême](/Robert_of_Bell%C3%AAme,_3rd_Earl_of_Shrewsbury). &#91;107&#93;

With the settlement meticulously reached between [Henry I](/Henry_I_of_England) and [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), and indeed other Welsh lords, the formal division of [Wales](/Wales) into *Pura Wallia* (the lands remaining under Welsh control) and *[Marchia Wallie](/Welsh_Marches)* (Welsh lands now under Norman control) came into existence. Author and historian [John Davies](/John_Davies_(historian)) notes, with characteristic precision, that this border, while shifting "in one direction and in the other" on occasion, remarkably remained more or less stable for almost the next two hundred years. &#91;117&#93; A testament to the enduring, if uneasy, nature of these agreements.

After generations of incessant, grinding warfare, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), with a pragmatism born of experience, began the arduous reconstruction of Gwynedd, intent on finally bringing a measure of stability to his beleaguered country. According to Davies, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) sought to grant his people the rare luxury of peace, allowing them "to plant their crops in the full confidence that they would be able to harvest them." &#91;108&#93; He diligently consolidated royal authority across north [Wales](/Wales), and, in a humanitarian gesture that was also strategically astute, offered sanctuary to displaced Welsh people from the Perfeddwlad, particularly from [Rhos](/Rhos_(north_Wales)), a region at the time relentlessly harassed by [Richard, 2nd Earl of Chester](/Richard_d%27Avranches,_2nd_Earl_of_Chester). &#91;118&#93;

Understandably alarmed by [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s growing influence and consolidating authority in north [Wales](/Wales), and under the convenient pretext that [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) was sheltering rebels from [Rhos](/Rhos_(north_Wales)) against Chester, [Henry I](/Henry_I_of_England) rather predictably launched another campaign against Gwynedd and [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) in 1116. This formidable force included a [vanguard](/Avant-garde) commanded by King [Alexander I of Scotland](/Alexander_I_of_Scotland). &#91;107&#93; &#91;108&#93; While [Owain ap Cadwgan](/Owain_ap_Cadwgan) of [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion) sought refuge in Gwynedd's unforgiving mountains, [Maredudd ap Bleddyn](/Maredudd_ap_Bleddyn) of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) made a pragmatic peace with the English king as the Norman army advanced. &#91;107&#93; In the face of such a vast [host](/Army) brought into [Wales](/Wales), there were, rather anticlimactically, no major battles or skirmishes fought. Instead, [Owain](/Owain_ap_Cadwgan) and [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) entered into truce negotiations. [Owain ap Cadwgan](/Owain_ap_Cadwgan) regained royal favour with relative ease. [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), however, was compelled to render [homage](/Homage_(feudal)) and [fealty](/Fealty) and pay a rather heavy fine, though he, crucially, lost neither land nor prestige. &#91;118&#93; A minor setback, but a necessary one.

This invasion left a lasting impact on [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), who by 1116 was already in his 60s and contending with failing eyesight. For the remainder of his life, while [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) continued to nominally rule in Gwynedd, the practical leadership of Gwynedd's army, after 1120, fell to his capable sons: Cadwallon, [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd), and [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd). &#91;107&#93; [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s astute policy, which his sons would diligently execute and which later rulers of Gwynedd would wisely adopt, was to meticulously recover Gwynedd's primacy without overtly antagonizing the English crown. &#91;107&#93; &#91;118&#93; A delicate dance on the precipice of war.

### The expansion of Gwynedd

In 1120, a minor border skirmish, the kind that often escalated into larger conflicts, erupted between Llywarch ab Owain, the lord of a [commote](/Commote) in the [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd) [cantref](/Cantref), and Hywel ab Ithel, the lord of [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog) and [Rhos](/Rhos_(north_Wales)). This local dispute, predictably, drew [Powys](/Powys) and Chester into a broader conflict in the Perfeddwlad. [Powys](/Powys) dispatched a force of 400 warriors to aid its ally, [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog), while Chester sent Norman knights from Rhuddlan to assist [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd). The bloody [Battle of Maes Maen Cymro](/Battle_of_Maes_Maen_Cymro), fought approximately 1 mile (1.5 kilometres) northwest of Ruthin, concluded with Llywarch ab Owain slain and the defeat of [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd). However, it proved to be a [pyrrhic victory](/Pyrrhic_victory), as the battle also left Hywel ab Ithel mortally wounded. With him being the last of his line, his death six weeks later left [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog) and [Rhos](/Rhos_(north_Wales)) bereft of lordship. [Powys](/Powys), however, lacked the strength to garrison these newly vacant territories, nor was Chester able to exert significant influence inland from its coastal holdings of Rhuddlan and Degannwy. With [Rhufoniog](/Rhufoniog) and [Rhos](/Rhos_(north_Wales)) effectively abandoned, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), with characteristic opportunism, swiftly annexed the [cantrefs](/Cantref). &#91;118&#93;

Upon the death of Einion ap Cadwgan, lord of [Meirionnydd](/Meirionnydd), a bitter quarrel engulfed his kinsmen over who should succeed him. [Meirionnydd](/Meirionnydd) was, at this time, a vassal [cantref](/Cantref) of [Powys](/Powys), and the ruling family there a [cadet](/Cadet) branch of the [Mathrafal](/Mathrafal) house of [Powys](/Powys). [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), ever alert to such opportunities, granted license to his sons Cadwallon and Owain to exploit the dynastic strife that had erupted in [Meirionnydd](/Meirionnydd). The brothers, with calculated aggression, raided [Meirionnydd](/Meirionnydd), a move that proved as disruptive to the Lord of [Powys](/Powys) there as it had in the Perfeddwlad. However, it would not be until 1136 that the [cantref](/Cantref) was firmly brought within Gwynedd's control. Perhaps fueled by their perceived slight due to [Powys](/Powys)'s support of Earl Hugh of Chester, Gwynedd's rival, Cadwallon, in 1124, slew the three rulers of [Dyffryn Clwyd](/Dyffryn_Clwyd), who were, rather inconveniently, his maternal uncles. This act brought the [cantref](/Cantref) firmly under Gwynedd's [vassalage](/Vassalage) that very year. &#91;118&#93; And in 1125, Cadwallon continued his ruthless consolidation, slaying the grandsons of [Edwin ap Goronwy of Tegeingl](/Edwin_of_Tegeingl), thereby leaving [Tegeingl](/Tegeingl) bereft of lordship. &#91;116&#93; However, in 1132, while on campaign in the [commote](/Commote) of [Nanheudwy](/Nanheudwy), near [Llangollen](/Llangollen), the 'victorious' Cadwallon suffered a decisive defeat in battle and was slain by an army from [Powys](/Powys). This setback abruptly checked Gwynedd's expansion for a time, "much to the relief of the men of Powys," as historian Sir [John Edward Lloyd](/John_Edward_Lloyd) (J.E Lloyd) rather dryly observed. &#91;118&#93;

In 1136, a significant campaign was launched from Gwynedd against the Normans, ostensibly in revenge for the execution of [Gwenllian ferch Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gwenllian_ferch_Gruffudd), the wife of the King of [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth) and, rather pertinently, the daughter of [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) himself. When word reached Gwynedd of Gwenllian's tragic death and the concurrent revolt in Gwent, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s sons, Owain and Cadwaladr, wasted no time. They swiftly invaded Norman-controlled [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion), seizing [Llanfihangle](/Llanfihangel_y_Creuddyn), [Aberystwyth](/Aberystwyth), and [Llanbadarn](/Llanbadarn_Fawr,_Ceredigion). &#91;119&#93; &#91;120&#93; Upon liberating Llanbadarn, one local chronicler, clearly impressed, hailed Owain and Cadwaladr both as "bold lions, virtuous, fearless and wise, who guard the churches and their indwellers, defenders of the poor [who] overcome their enemies, affording a safest retreat to all those who seek their protection." &#91;119&#93; The brothers diligently restored the Welsh monks of Llanbadarn, who had been unceremoniously displaced by monks from Gloucester brought in by the Normans who had, for a time, controlled [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion). By late September 1136, a vast Welsh host had gathered in [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion), a formidable alliance that included the combined forces of Gwynedd, [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth), and [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys). They met the Norman army at the decisive [Battle of Crug Mawr](/Battle_of_Crug_Mawr) near [Cardigan Castle](/Cardigan_Castle). The engagement quickly devolved into a rout, culminating in a resounding defeat for the Normans. &#91;119&#93;

[Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s remains were [interred](/Interment) in a tomb in the [presbytery](/Presbytery_(architecture)) of [Bangor Cathedral](/Bangor_Cathedral)

When their father, [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), finally died in 1137, his sons Owain and Cadwaladr were, rather fittingly, still on campaign, engaged in a second offensive in [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion). They successfully captured the castles of [Ystrad Meurig](/Ystrad_Meurig), [Lampeter](/Lampeter) (known then as Stephen's Castle), and Castell Hywell (Humphries Castle). &#91;119&#93; [Gruffudd ap Cynan](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan), despite the persistent chaos of the era, left behind a realm in Gwynedd that was more stable than it had been for over a century. No foreign army had managed to cross the [Conwy](/Conwy) into upper Gwynedd during his long reign. The relative stability he achieved allowed the Welsh people of Gwynedd, for a precious time, to plan for the future without the constant, gnawing fear that their homes and harvests would "go to the flames" from relentless invaders. &#91;121&#93; A rare, and much-appreciated, respite.

Settlements, reflecting this newfound stability, began to shift from ephemeral timber structures to more permanent buildings of stone. Stone churches, in particular, began to appear across Gwynedd, with so many meticulously [limewashed](/Whitewash) that, as one contemporary account rather poetically put it, "Gwynedd was bespangled with them as is the [firmament](/Firmament) with stars." [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) himself had commissioned the construction of stone churches at his royal manors, and Lloyd suggests that Gruffudd's example inspired the widespread rebuilding of churches in stone in places like [Penmon](/Penmon), [Aberdaron](/Aberdaron), and [Towyn](/Towyn), often adopting the prevailing [Norman fashion](/Norman_architecture). &#91;121&#93;

[Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan) was also instrumental in promoting the primacy of the [Episcopal See](/Episcopal_See) of [Bangor](/Bangor,_Gwynedd) within Gwynedd. He generously funded the construction of [Bangor Cathedral](/Bangor_Cathedral) during the episcopate of [David the Scot](/David_the_Scot), who served as [Bishop of Bangor](/Bishop_of_Bangor) between 1120 and 1139. His enduring legacy was marked by his own remains being [interred](/Interment) in a tomb within the [presbytery](/Presbytery_(architecture)) of [Bangor Cathedral](/Bangor_Cathedral). &#91;121&#93; A final, stone-bound assertion of his enduring influence.

### Owain Gwynedd

[Owain ap Gruffudd](/Owain_Gwynedd) (known to history as [Owain Gwynedd](/Owain_Gwynedd), c.&#8201;1100&#160;–&#160;23 or 28&#160;November&#160;1170 &#91;122&#93; &#91;123&#93;), with the predictable adherence to [Welsh law](/Welsh_law), the *Cyfraith Hywel*, or Laws of Hywel, succeeded his father to the greater portion of Gwynedd. He became known as [Owain Gwynedd](/Owain_Gwynedd) to distinguish him from another Owain ap Gruffudd, the [Mathrafal](/House_of_Mathrafal) ruler of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys), who was known, less grandly, as [Owain Cyfeiliog](/Owain_Cyfeiliog). &#91;124&#93; [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd), [Gruffudd](/Gruffudd_ap_Cynan)'s youngest son, inherited the [commote](/Commote) of [Aberffraw](/Aberffraw) on Ynys Môn (now [Anglesey](/Anglesey)), as well as the recently conquered [Meirionydd](/Meirionnydd) and northern [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion)—specifically, the territory between the rivers Aeron and the Dyfi. &#91;125&#93; A tidy division, for a time.

By 1141, [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) and Madog ap Maredudd of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys) led a Welsh [vanguard](/Avant-garde) as allies of the Earl of Chester in the [Battle of Lincoln (1141)](/Battle_of_Lincoln_(1141)). They participated in the rout that resulted in [Stephen of England](/Stephen,_King_of_England) being held prisoner by Empress Matilda for a year. [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd), however, with a prudence that would become his hallmark, chose not to participate in the battle, keeping the majority of Gwynedd's army safely at home. &#91;126&#93; &#91;j&#93;

[Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) and [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) inevitably came to blows in 1143 when [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) was implicated in the murder of King [Anarawd ap Gruffudd](/Anarawd_ap_Gruffudd) of [Deheubarth](/Deheubarth), who was not only Owain's ally but also his prospective son-in-law, on the very eve of Anarawd's wedding to Owain's daughter. &#91;127&#93; &#91;128&#93; [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) had carefully pursued a diplomatic policy of binding other Welsh rulers to Gwynedd through strategic dynastic marriages, and [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd)'s border dispute and subsequent murder of Anarawd severely threatened Owain's meticulous efforts and his crucial credibility. &#91;120&#93; As the established ruler of Gwynedd, [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) promptly stripped [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) of his lands, dispatching his own son [Hywel](/Hywel_ab_Owain_Gwynedd) to [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion), where he, with brutal efficiency, burned Cadwaladr's castle at Aberystwyth. [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) fled to [Ireland](/Ireland) and, predictably, hired a Norse fleet from [Dublin](/Dublin), bringing the fleet to Abermenai to compel [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) to reinstate him. &#91;127&#93; This same fleet of ships would have been considered a formidable force, capable of facing the fleet of [Stephen, King of England](/Stephen,_King_of_England), as well as the Irish and Scottish forces at [Abermenai Point](/Abermenai_Point) earlier in 1142. &#91;129&#93;

Taking advantage of this rather convenient brotherly strife, and perhaps with the tacit understanding of [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd), the marcher lords mounted opportunistic incursions into [Wales](/Wales). &#91;128&#93; Realizing the wider, and more dangerous, ramifications of the war unfolding before him, [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) and [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) eventually came to terms and reconciled, with [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) being restored to his lands. &#91;127&#93; &#91;128&#93; This fragile peace between the brothers held until 1147, when an unrecorded event (history, ever coy, sometimes leaves out the juicy details) occurred, leading Owain's sons [Hywel](/Hywel_ab_Owain_Gwynedd) and [Cynan](/Cynan_ab_Owain_Gwynedd) to drive [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) out of [Meirionydd](/Meirionnydd) and [Ceredigion](/Kingdom_of_Ceredigion). [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) retreated, rather predictably, to Môn ([Anglesey](/Anglesey)). &#91;127&#93; Again, an accord was reached, with [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) retaining [Aberffraw](/Aberffraw) until a more serious breach occurred in 1153, at which point he was forced into exile in [England](/Kingdom_of_England), where his wife was the sister of [Gilbert de Clare, 1st Earl of Hertford](/Gilbert_de_Clare,_1st_Earl_of_Hertford) and the niece of [Ranulf de Gernon, 4th Earl of Chester](/Ranulf_de_Gernon,_4th_Earl_of_Chester). &#91;127&#93; &#91;128&#93; A well-connected exile, at least.

In 1146, rather unwelcome news reached [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd): his favoured eldest son and designated heir, [Rhun ab Owain Gwynedd](/Rhun_ab_Owain_Gwynedd), had died. [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) was overcome with grief, falling into a deep depression from which, it seemed, none could console him. That is, until news reached him that [Mold Castle](/Mold,_Flintshire) in [Tegeingl](/Tegeingl) had fallen to Gwynedd, "[reminding Owain] that he had still a country for which to live," as historian Sir [John Edward Lloyd](/John_Edward_Lloyd) so eloquently, and rather cynically, put it. &#91;130&#93; The demands of state, it seems, often trump personal sorrow.

Between 1148 and 1151, [Owain I of Gwynedd](/Owain_Gwynedd) engaged in a series of conflicts against Madog ap Maredudd of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys), who also happened to be Owain's son-in-law, and against the Earl of Chester, all for control of [Iâl (Yale)](/I%C3%A2l). [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd), with characteristic strategic acumen, managed to secure Rhuddlan Castle and all of [Tegeingl](/Tegeingl) from Chester. &#91;131&#93; &#91;122&#93; "By 1154 [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) had brought his men within sight of the red towers of the great city on the [Dee](/River_Dee,_Wales)," Lloyd noted, a clear indication of his burgeoning power. &#91;131&#93;

Having spent three years consolidating his authority across the vast [Angevin Empire](/Angevin_Empire), [Henry II of England](/Henry_II_of_England) finally resolved on a comprehensive strategy against [Owain I of Gwynedd](/Owain_Gwynedd) by 1157. By this point, Owain's enemies had, rather conveniently, flocked to Henry II's camp. These included his wayward brother [Cadwaladr](/Cadwaladr_ap_Gruffydd) and, significantly, the crucial support of Madog of [Powys](/Kingdom_of_Powys). &#91;k&#93; [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) raised his formidable feudal host and marched into [Wales](/Wales) from Chester. [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) strategically positioned himself and his army at Dinas Basing ([Basingwerk](/Basingwerk_Abbey)), effectively barring the direct road to Rhuddlan. He had, with foresight, set up a trap, anticipating that [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) would send his army along the coastal road while attempting to out-flank [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) by crossing through the woods. The King of Gwynedd, however, had, with impressive foresight, anticipated this move and dispatched his sons [Dafydd ab Owain Gwynedd](/Dafydd_ab_Owain_Gwynedd) and [Cynan](/Cynan_ab_Owain_Gwynedd) into the woods with a substantial force, catching [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) entirely unaware. &#91;132&#93; &#91;133&#93;

In the ensuing melee, [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) might well have been slain, had not [Roger de Clare, 2nd Earl of Hertford](/Roger_de_Clare,_2nd_Earl_of_Hertford), rather fortuitously, rescued the king. [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) retreated and made his way back to his main army, which was, by now, slowly advancing towards Rhuddlan. Not wishing to engage the formidable Norman army directly, [Owain](/Owain_Gwynedd) strategically repositioned himself, first at St. Asaph, then further west, thereby clearing the road for [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) to enter into Rhuddlan "ingloriously." &#91;132&#93; Once in Rhuddlan, [Henry II](/Henry_II_of_England) received the rather disheartening news that his naval expedition, instead of meeting him at Degannwy or Rhuddlan as planned, had, with predictable opportunism, gone to plunder [Anglesey](/Anglesey). This led to the [Battle of Ewloe](/Battle_of_Ewloe), an engagement that has since been commemorated with a plaque 850 years after the battle of 1157, during 2007. &#91;134&#93;

In a later, perhaps self-serving, letter to the [Byzantine emperor](/List_of_Byzantine_emperors), [Henry](/Henry_II_of_England) probably recalled these rather frustrating experiences when he wrote, with a grudging admiration: "A people called Welsh, so bold and ferocious that, when unarmed, they do not fear to encounter an armed force, being ready to shed their blood in defence of their country, and to sacrifice their lives for renown." &#91;135&#93; A rather telling compliment from a defeated foe.

